[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Exploring Groovy clearCache**\n\nI'm trying to clarify if ClearCaches is meant for Groovy and whether the GroovyClassLoader has a clearCache method. There might be a way to add testImplementation for Groovy, but I need to stick with the current active coordinate.\n\nSo, I wonder if I should broaden it, but probably not. I'm considering the dynamic access metadata generation tool and how it merges library and test metadata. It seems the filter is designed to only track library metadata and not user code. I need to figure out if this includes test class methods accessed by Spring Boot.\n\n**Clarifying metadata and class naming**\n\nI'm thinking about how metadata for test classes might be generated during the build process, not necessarily among the resources. The native image compiles tests with their respective classes, so the configuration can include methods effectively. It’s important to avoid using \"$\" in test class or file names.\n\nI wonder if I can get around using inner classes by adding a top-level non-public class that doesn't use \"$\". So, having a package-private final class like ClearableCacheClassLoader in the same Java file would work better and maintain a single mapping without using \"$\".\n\n**Evaluating method access and class visibility**\n\nI'm considering if I need to use `AtomicBoolean` for thread safety in my classloader. Since it might be called on the same thread, a simple boolean is probably fine, and I can assert after the finally block. \n\nI’m wondering if a package-private method would be an issue, especially if the ClassLoader constructor is protected. If I getDeclaredMethod for \"clearCache\" in a package-private class, will it work? I should make the method public. But if the class is package-private, the method can still be public but inaccessible from `org.springframework.boot`.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_0790c